<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-slope-fields-intro" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Slope Fields</title>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       INTRO PROSE
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    So far we have been solving differential equations and writing down explicit formulas for solutions.
    That is powerful, but it is not always possible. Many differential equations are too complicated to
    solve by hand, and even when we can solve them, the formula alone does not always make it easy to
    picture what the solutions actually look like. In this section we develop a visual tool that lets us
    understand the behavior of solutions to a differential equation without solving it at all.
  </p>
  <p>
    The idea starts with something simple. If we have a differential equation
    <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = F(x, y)</m>, then at any point <m>(x, y)</m> in the plane, the equation
    tells us exactly what slope a solution passing through that point must have. We do not need to
    know the solution to know its slope. We just plug in <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
  </p>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       MOTIVATING EXAMPLE: dy/dx = 2y
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    Recall that the general solution to <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 2y</m> is <m>y = Ce^{2x}</m>.
    Let's focus on one specific solution, <m>y = e^{2x}</m> (that is, <m>C = 1</m>).
    Since <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 2y</m>, the slope of the tangent line to this curve
    at any point is just twice the <m>y</m>-value at that point. Use the interactive
    below to explore this. Try changing both the solution curve (via <m>C</m>)
    and the <m>y</m>-value to see how the slope responds.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="fig-tangent-slope-slider">
    <caption>
      The solution curve <m>y = Ce^{2x}</m> with a tangent line at a chosen point.
      Notice that the slope <m>dy/dx = 2y</m> depends only on the <m>y</m>-value,
      not on which curve you are on or what <m>x</m> is.
    </caption>
    <interactive xml:id="interactive-tangent-slope" iframe="interactive-tangent-slope.html" width="100%" aspect="3:2">
      <static>
        <p>
          An interactive graph showing the solution curve <m>y = Ce^{2x}</m> with sliders
          for <m>C</m> and a point on the curve. The tangent line at the chosen point updates
          to show slope <m>dy/dx = 2y</m>.
        </p>
      </static>
    </interactive>
  </figure>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       TRANSITION PROSE: into slope fields
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    Here is the key observation from the interactive above: the slope <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 2y</m>
    depends only on the <m>y</m>-value, not on the specific solution curve or the <m>x</m>-value.
    This means that at every point <m>(x, y)</m> in the plane with the same <m>y</m>-coordinate,
    the slope of any solution passing through that point is the same.
  </p>
  <p>
    This gives us a powerful idea. Even without knowing the solutions explicitly,
    we can draw a short line segment at every point <m>(x, y)</m> with slope equal to <m>2y</m>,
    just from knowing the <m>y</m>-value. The resulting picture is called a <term>slope field</term>.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-slope-field">
    <title>Slope Field</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>slope field</term> for a differential equation <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = F(x, y)</m>
        is a plot of short line segments drawn at a grid of points <m>(x, y)</m>,
        each with slope equal to <m>F(x, y)</m>. Together, these segments show the
        slope that any solution curve must have as it passes through each point.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       INTERACTIVE 2: building the slope field
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    Let's build the slope field for <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 2y</m> step by step.
    For each <m>y</m>-value, the slope is <m>2y</m> regardless of <m>x</m>,
    so every tick in the same row has the same slope.
    Press play to watch the slope field get drawn.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="fig-slope-field-build">
    <caption>
      Building the slope field for <m>dy/dx = 2y</m>. Each tick mark is drawn at a
      grid point <m>(x, y)</m> with slope <m>2y</m>. Notice that all ticks in the
      same row (same <m>y</m>) are parallel. The slope does not depend on <m>x</m>.
    </caption>
    <interactive xml:id="interactive-slope-field-build" iframe="interactive-slope-field-build.html" width="100%" aspect="3:2">
      <static>
        <p>
          An interactive slope field for <m>dy/dx = 2y</m> that builds up one tick mark
          at a time when the play button is pressed. Tick marks are horizontal along
          <m>y = 0</m>, slope upward for <m>y > 0</m>, and slope downward for <m>y \lt 0</m>.
        </p>
      </static>
    </interactive>
  </figure>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PROSE: transition to solution curves
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    In practice, computers generate slope fields with far more points than we could
    draw by hand. The interactive below shows a dense slope field for <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 2y</m>.
    Use the slider to set an initial value <m>y(0)</m>, then press play to watch the
    corresponding solution curve trace itself through the field, following the arrows and
    connecting the dots. This is the fundamental idea: the slope field tells you
    which way any solution must travel at every point.
  </p>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       INTERACTIVE 3: dense slope field + trajectory tracing
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <figure xml:id="fig-slope-field-trajectory">
    <caption>
      A dense slope field for <m>dy/dx = 2y</m>. Set the initial value <m>y(0)</m>
      with the slider, then press play to trace the solution curve through the field.
      Notice how the curve always aligns with the tick marks as it travels.
    </caption>
    <interactive xml:id="interactive-slope-field-trajectory" iframe="interactive-slope-field-trajectory.html" width="100%" aspect="3:2">
      <static>
        <p>
          An interactive dense slope field for <m>dy/dx = 2y</m> with a slider for
          the initial value <m>y(0)</m>. Pressing play traces the solution curve
          <m>y = y(0) \cdot e^{2x}</m> through the field, showing how the curve
          follows the direction indicated by the slope field.
        </p>
      </static>
    </interactive>
  </figure>

